  sodium: 1920 mg
cuisine: East Asia
---

Bring a large #pot of water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Trim and thinly
slice @scallions{2%unit}, separating whites from greens. Roughly chop
@cashews{1%ounce}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large pan over medium-high
heat. Add broccoli; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring
frequently, until browned and tender, ~{4-7%minutes}.

Add scallion whites, @shredded carrots{4%ounce}, and @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}.
Cook, stirring frequently and lowering heat if browning too quickly, until
veggies are just tender and fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

> TIP: If pan seems dry, add a drizzle of oil.

While veggies cook, in a #small bowl{}, combine @sweet Thai chili sauce{2%ounce},
@Vidalia onion paste{1/2%ounce}, half the @rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, half the
@soy sauce{2%tablespoon}, and 1/4 cup water.

> For 4 servings: use all the vinegar, all the soy sauce, and 1/2 cup water.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Drain noodles, shaking off any excess water, and transfer to pan with veggies.
Add soy-chili mixture, half the cashews, and @butter{1%tablespoon}. Toss until
butter has melted and noodles are thoroughly coated, ~{30-60%seconds}. Taste and
season with salt and pepper if desired.

> For 4 servings: use 2 tablespoons butter.

Divide lo mein between shallow bowls; garnish with scallion greens and remaining
cashews. Serve.